{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":212,"text":"When I was a young man, I spent six years"},{"time":2285,"text":"of wild adventure in the tropics"},{"time":4398,"text":"working as an investigative journalist"},{"time":6526,"text":"in some of the most bewitching parts of the world."},{"time":9911,"text":"I was as reckless and foolish as only young men can be."},{"time":13110,"text":"This is why wars get fought."},{"time":14648,"text":"But I also felt more alive than I've ever done since."},{"time":18875,"text":"And when I came home, I found the scope of my existence"},{"time":22768,"text":"gradually diminishing"},{"time":24751,"text":"until loading the dishwasher seemed like an interesting challenge."},{"time":29197,"text":"And I found myself sort of"},{"time":31337,"text":"scratching at the walls of life,"},{"time":33394,"text":"as if I was trying to find a way out"},{"time":35432,"text":"into a wider space beyond."},{"time":37319,"text":"I was, I believe, ecologically bored."}]},{"cues":[{"time":41850,"text":"Now, we evolved in rather more challenging times than these,"},{"time":46331,"text":"in a world of horns and tusks and fangs and claws."},{"time":51157,"text":"And we still possess the fear and the courage"},{"time":53753,"text":"and the aggression required to navigate those times."},{"time":56946,"text":"But in our comfortable, safe, crowded lands,"},{"time":61630,"text":"we have few opportunities to exercise them"},{"time":64613,"text":"without harming other people."},{"time":67765,"text":"And this was the sort of constraint that I found myself"},{"time":71903,"text":"bumping up against."},{"time":74153,"text":"To conquer uncertainty,"},{"time":76765,"text":"to know what comes next,"},{"time":80083,"text":"that's almost been the dominant aim of industrialized societies,"},{"time":84653,"text":"and having got there, or almost got there,"},{"time":88253,"text":"we have just encountered a new set of unmet needs."},{"time":91616,"text":"We've privileged safety over experience"},{"time":94618,"text":"and we've gained a lot in doing so,"},{"time":97122,"text":"but I think we've lost something too."}]},{"cues":[{"time":100130,"text":"Now, I don't romanticize evolutionary time."},{"time":102932,"text":"I'm already beyond the lifespan of most hunter-gatherers,"},{"time":106450,"text":"and the outcome of a mortal combat between me"},{"time":109679,"text":"myopically stumbling around with a stone-tipped spear"},{"time":112592,"text":"and an enraged giant aurochs"},{"time":115074,"text":"isn't very hard to predict."},{"time":117556,"text":"Nor was it authenticity that I was looking for."},{"time":120552,"text":"I don't find that a useful or even intelligible concept."},{"time":123692,"text":"I just wanted a richer and rawer life"},{"time":127618,"text":"than I've been able to lead in Britain, or, indeed,"},{"time":130114,"text":"that we can lead in most parts of the industrialized world."}]},{"cues":[{"time":133526,"text":"And it was only when I stumbled across an unfamiliar word"},{"time":139032,"text":"that I began to understand what I was looking for."},{"time":142637,"text":"And as soon as I found that word,"},{"time":145291,"text":"I realized that I wanted to devote"},{"time":147319,"text":"much of the rest of my life to it."}]},{"cues":[{"time":151074,"text":"The word is \"rewilding,\""},{"time":154575,"text":"and even though rewilding is a young word,"},{"time":157357,"text":"it already has several definitions."},{"time":159224,"text":"But there are two in particular that fascinate me."},{"time":163260,"text":"The first one is the mass restoration"},{"time":167211,"text":"of ecosystems."}]},{"cues":[{"time":169866,"text":"One of the most exciting scientific findings"},{"time":172836,"text":"of the past half century"},{"time":174606,"text":"has been the discovery of widespread trophic cascades."},{"time":179352,"text":"A trophic cascade is an ecological process"},{"time":182530,"text":"which starts at the top of the food chain"},{"time":184905,"text":"and tumbles all the way down to the bottom,"},{"time":188200,"text":"and the classic example is what happened"},{"time":190543,"text":"in the Yellowstone National Park in the United States"},{"time":193354,"text":"when wolves were reintroduced in 1995."},{"time":197443,"text":"Now, we all know that wolves kill various species of animals,"},{"time":201878,"text":"but perhaps we're slightly less aware"},{"time":204277,"text":"that they give life to many others."},{"time":208115,"text":"It sounds strange, but just follow me for a while."},{"time":211228,"text":"Before the wolves turned up,"},{"time":213054,"text":"they'd been absent for 70 years."},{"time":214713,"text":"The numbers of deer, because there was nothing to hunt them,"},{"time":217778,"text":"had built up and built up in the Yellowstone Park,"},{"time":220532,"text":"and despite efforts by humans to control them,"},{"time":223623,"text":"they'd managed to reduce much of the vegetation there"},{"time":226318,"text":"to almost nothing, they'd just grazed it away."},{"time":229739,"text":"But as soon as the wolves arrived,"},{"time":231934,"text":"even though they were few in number,"},{"time":233761,"text":"they started to have the most remarkable effects."},{"time":237660,"text":"First, of course, they killed some of the deer,"},{"time":239831,"text":"but that wasn't the major thing."},{"time":241643,"text":"Much more significantly,"},{"time":243674,"text":"they radically changed the behavior of the deer."},{"time":246873,"text":"The deer started avoiding certain parts of the park,"},{"time":249786,"text":"the places where they could be trapped most easily,"},{"time":252009,"text":"particularly the valleys and the gorges,"},{"time":254748,"text":"and immediately those places started to regenerate."},{"time":257937,"text":"In some areas, the height of the trees"},{"time":260336,"text":"quintupled in just six years."},{"time":263348,"text":"Bare valley sides quickly became forests of aspen"},{"time":267415,"text":"and willow and cottonwood."},{"time":269686,"text":"And as soon as that happened,"},{"time":271464,"text":"the birds started moving in."},{"time":273622,"text":"The number of songbirds, of migratory birds,"},{"time":276043,"text":"started to increase greatly."},{"time":278117,"text":"The number of beavers started to increase,"},{"time":280174,"text":"because beavers like to eat the trees."},{"time":282855,"text":"And beavers, like wolves, are ecosystem engineers."},{"time":286083,"text":"They create niches for other species."},{"time":288962,"text":"And the dams they built in the rivers"},{"time":291174,"text":"provided habitats for otters and muskrats"},{"time":294108,"text":"and ducks and fish and reptiles and amphibians."},{"time":298289,"text":"The wolves killed coyotes, and as a result of that,"},{"time":302394,"text":"the number of rabbits and mice began to rise,"},{"time":304856,"text":"which meant more hawks, more weasels,"},{"time":307766,"text":"more foxes, more badgers."},{"time":310165,"text":"Ravens and bald eagles came down to feed"},{"time":312652,"text":"on the carrion that the wolves had left."},{"time":314888,"text":"Bears fed on it too, and their population began to rise as well,"},{"time":318597,"text":"partly also because there were more berries"},{"time":320940,"text":"growing on the regenerating shrubs,"},{"time":323252,"text":"and the bears reinforced the impact of the wolves"},{"time":326483,"text":"by killing some of the calves of the deer."}]},{"cues":[{"time":330882,"text":"But here's where it gets really interesting."},{"time":334558,"text":"The wolves changed the behavior of the rivers."},{"time":339843,"text":"They began to meander less."},{"time":341530,"text":"There was less erosion. The channels narrowed."},{"time":345153,"text":"More pools formed, more riffle sections,"},{"time":347548,"text":"all of which were great for wildlife habitats."},{"time":349779,"text":"The rivers changed"},{"time":351981,"text":"in response to the wolves,"},{"time":354193,"text":"and the reason was that the regenerating forests"},{"time":357838,"text":"stabilized the banks so that they collapsed less often,"},{"time":361529,"text":"so that the rivers became more fixed in their course."},{"time":364849,"text":"Similarly, by driving the deer out of some places"},{"time":368576,"text":"and the vegetation recovering on the valley sides,"},{"time":372932,"text":"there was less soil erosion,"},{"time":374345,"text":"because the vegetation stabilized that as well."},{"time":377881,"text":"So the wolves, small in number,"},{"time":381242,"text":"transformed not just the ecosystem"},{"time":384205,"text":"of the Yellowstone National Park, this huge area of land,"},{"time":387307,"text":"but also its physical geography."}]},{"cues":[{"time":391525,"text":"Whales in the southern oceans"},{"time":393149,"text":"have similarly wide-ranging effects."},{"time":395652,"text":"One of the many post-rational excuses"},{"time":398519,"text":"made by the Japanese government for killing whales"},{"time":401509,"text":"is that they said, \"Well, the number of fish and krill will rise"},{"time":404643,"text":"and then there'll be more for people to eat.\""},{"time":406881,"text":"Well, it's a stupid excuse, but it sort of"},{"time":408892,"text":"kind of makes sense, doesn't it,"},{"time":410261,"text":"because you'd think that whales eat huge amounts"},{"time":412385,"text":"of fish and krill, so obviously take the whales away,"},{"time":414547,"text":"there'll be more fish and krill."},{"time":416609,"text":"But the opposite happened."},{"time":419002,"text":"You take the whales away,"},{"time":420331,"text":"and the number of krill collapses."},{"time":423182,"text":"Why would that possibly have happened?"},{"time":425275,"text":"Well, it now turns out that the whales are crucial"},{"time":428415,"text":"to sustaining that entire ecosystem,"},{"time":431728,"text":"and one of the reasons for this"},{"time":433457,"text":"is that they often feed at depth"},{"time":435557,"text":"and then they come up to the surface and produce"},{"time":437339,"text":"what biologists politely call large fecal plumes,"},{"time":441525,"text":"huge explosions of poop right across the surface waters,"},{"time":445958,"text":"up in the photic zone, where there's enough light"},{"time":449274,"text":"to allow photosynthesis to take place,"},{"time":452446,"text":"and those great plumes of fertilizer"},{"time":455390,"text":"stimulate the growth of phytoplankton,"},{"time":457382,"text":"the plant plankton at the bottom of the food chain,"},{"time":459296,"text":"which stimulate the growth of zooplankton,"},{"time":461394,"text":"which feed the fish and the krill and all the rest of it."},{"time":463691,"text":"The other thing that whales do is that,"},{"time":465825,"text":"as they're plunging up and down through the water column,"},{"time":468554,"text":"they're kicking the phytoplankton"},{"time":470922,"text":"back up towards the surface"},{"time":472372,"text":"where it can continue to survive and reproduce."},{"time":475486,"text":"And interestingly, well, we know"},{"time":478114,"text":"that plant plankton in the oceans"},{"time":481051,"text":"absorb carbon from the atmosphere --"},{"time":482858,"text":"the more plant plankton there are,"},{"time":484401,"text":"the more carbon they absorb --"},{"time":486080,"text":"and eventually they filter down into the abyss"},{"time":489162,"text":"and remove that carbon from the atmospheric system."},{"time":492542,"text":"Well, it seems that when whales were at their historic populations,"},{"time":496843,"text":"they were probably responsible for sequestering"},{"time":499852,"text":"some tens of millions of tons of carbon"},{"time":503645,"text":"every year from the atmosphere."}]},{"cues":[{"time":506334,"text":"And when you look at it like that, you think,"},{"time":509561,"text":"wait a minute, here are the wolves"},{"time":511420,"text":"changing the physical geography of the Yellowstone National Park."},{"time":514437,"text":"Here are the whales changing"},{"time":516296,"text":"the composition of the atmosphere."},{"time":518936,"text":"You begin to see that possibly,"},{"time":521246,"text":"the evidence supporting James Lovelock's Gaia hypothesis,"},{"time":524927,"text":"which conceives of the world as a coherent,"},{"time":527514,"text":"self-regulating organism,"},{"time":529444,"text":"is beginning, at the ecosystem level, to accumulate."}]},{"cues":[{"time":535178,"text":"Trophic cascades"},{"time":537446,"text":"tell us that the natural world"},{"time":539507,"text":"is even more fascinating and complex than we thought it was."},{"time":544253,"text":"They tell us that when you take away the large animals,"},{"time":547985,"text":"you are left with a radically different ecosystem"},{"time":551177,"text":"to one which retains its large animals."},{"time":554349,"text":"And they make, in my view, a powerful case"},{"time":557630,"text":"for the reintroduction of missing species."},{"time":561783,"text":"Rewilding, to me,"},{"time":563859,"text":"means bringing back some of the missing plants and animals."},{"time":567157,"text":"It means taking down the fences,"},{"time":568469,"text":"it means blocking the drainage ditches,"},{"time":570493,"text":"it means preventing commercial fishing in some large areas of sea,"},{"time":573757,"text":"but otherwise stepping back."},{"time":577171,"text":"It has no view as to what a right ecosystem"},{"time":580981,"text":"or a right assemblage of species looks like."},{"time":583682,"text":"It doesn't try to produce a heath or a meadow"},{"time":587461,"text":"or a rain forest or a kelp garden or a coral reef."},{"time":592147,"text":"It lets nature decide,"},{"time":594164,"text":"and nature, by and large, is pretty good at deciding."}]},{"cues":[{"time":597983,"text":"Now, I mentioned that there are two definitions"},{"time":600258,"text":"of rewilding that interest me."},{"time":602104,"text":"The other one"},{"time":603361,"text":"is the rewilding of human life."},{"time":606384,"text":"And I don't see this as an alternative"},{"time":608447,"text":"to civilization."},{"time":610371,"text":"I believe we can enjoy the benefits of advanced technology,"},{"time":613771,"text":"as we're doing now, but at the same time, if we choose,"},{"time":617610,"text":"have access to a richer and wilder life of adventure"},{"time":622626,"text":"when we want to because"},{"time":624209,"text":"there would be wonderful, rewilded habitats."}]},{"cues":[{"time":628605,"text":"And the opportunities for this"},{"time":630389,"text":"are developing more rapidly than you might think possible."},{"time":635380,"text":"There's one estimate which suggests that in the United States,"},{"time":638359,"text":"two thirds of the land which was once forested and then cleared"},{"time":642044,"text":"has become reforested as loggers and farmers have retreated,"},{"time":645547,"text":"particularly from the eastern half of the country."},{"time":648560,"text":"There's another one which suggests"},{"time":650217,"text":"that 30 million hectares of land in Europe,"},{"time":653680,"text":"an area the size of Poland,"},{"time":656187,"text":"will be vacated by farmers"},{"time":658018,"text":"between 2000 and 2030."}]},{"cues":[{"time":661340,"text":"Now, faced with opportunities like that,"},{"time":664876,"text":"does it not seem a little unambitious"},{"time":667047,"text":"to be thinking only of bringing back wolves, lynx,"},{"time":670761,"text":"bears, beavers, bison, boar, moose,"},{"time":674360,"text":"and all the other species which are already beginning"},{"time":676185,"text":"to move quite rapidly across Europe?"},{"time":679449,"text":"Perhaps we should also start thinking"},{"time":681973,"text":"about the return of some of our lost megafauna."}]},{"cues":[{"time":685962,"text":"What megafauna, you say?"},{"time":687894,"text":"Well, every continent had one,"},{"time":690463,"text":"apart from Antarctica."},{"time":691944,"text":"When Trafalgar Square in London was excavated,"},{"time":695582,"text":"the river gravels there were found"},{"time":697337,"text":"to be stuffed with the bones of hippopotamus,"},{"time":700887,"text":"rhinos, elephants, hyenas, lions."},{"time":704975,"text":"Yes, ladies and gentlemen,"},{"time":706349,"text":"there were lions in Trafalgar Square"},{"time":708545,"text":"long before Nelson's Column was built."},{"time":711751,"text":"All these species lived here"},{"time":714002,"text":"in the last interglacial period,"},{"time":716654,"text":"when temperatures were pretty similar to our own."},{"time":719515,"text":"It's not climate, largely,"},{"time":721588,"text":"which has got rid of the world's megafaunas."},{"time":725135,"text":"It's pressure from the human population"},{"time":727239,"text":"hunting and destroying their habitats"},{"time":729075,"text":"which has done so."}]},{"cues":[{"time":731126,"text":"And even so, you can still see the shadows"},{"time":734914,"text":"of these great beasts in our current ecosystems."},{"time":737622,"text":"Why is it that so many deciduous trees"},{"time":740575,"text":"are able to sprout from whatever point the trunk is broken?"},{"time":745133,"text":"Why is it that they can withstand the loss"},{"time":747202,"text":"of so much of their bark?"},{"time":748809,"text":"Why do understory trees,"},{"time":751752,"text":"which are subject to lower sheer forces from the wind"},{"time":756845,"text":"and have to carry less weight"},{"time":758576,"text":"than the big canopy trees,"},{"time":760978,"text":"why are they so much tougher and harder to break"},{"time":764097,"text":"than the canopy trees are?"},{"time":768506,"text":"Elephants."},{"time":770478,"text":"They are elephant-adapted."},{"time":772647,"text":"In Europe, for example,"},{"time":774935,"text":"they evolved to resist the straight-tusked elephant,"},{"time":778078,"text":"elephas antiquus, which was a great beast."},{"time":780366,"text":"It was related to the Asian elephant,"},{"time":782542,"text":"but it was a temperate animal, a temperate forest creature."},{"time":785111,"text":"It was a lot bigger than the Asian elephant."},{"time":787641,"text":"But why is it that some of our common shrubs"},{"time":790458,"text":"have spines which seem to be over-engineered"},{"time":793642,"text":"to resist browsing by deer?"},{"time":796305,"text":"Perhaps because they evolved"},{"time":798119,"text":"to resist browsing by rhinoceros."}]},{"cues":[{"time":801382,"text":"Isn't it an amazing thought"},{"time":803306,"text":"that every time you wander into a park"},{"time":806034,"text":"or down an avenue or through a leafy street,"},{"time":808881,"text":"you can see the shadows of these great beasts?"},{"time":812492,"text":"Paleoecology, the study of past ecosystems,"},{"time":816292,"text":"crucial to an understanding of our own,"},{"time":820350,"text":"feels like a portal through which you may pass"},{"time":823927,"text":"into an enchanted kingdom."},{"time":826859,"text":"And if we really are looking at areas of land"},{"time":830672,"text":"of the sort of sizes I've been talking about becoming available,"},{"time":834917,"text":"why not reintroduce some of our lost megafauna,"},{"time":837632,"text":"or at least species closely related to those"},{"time":839582,"text":"which have become extinct everywhere?"},{"time":842543,"text":"Why shouldn't all of us"},{"time":844852,"text":"have a Serengeti on our doorsteps?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":847805,"text":"And perhaps this is the most important thing"},{"time":850771,"text":"that rewilding offers us,"},{"time":852246,"text":"the most important thing that's missing from our lives:"},{"time":855840,"text":"hope."},{"time":857957,"text":"In motivating people to love and defend the natural world,"},{"time":862354,"text":"an ounce of hope is worth a ton of despair."},{"time":867164,"text":"The story rewilding tells us"},{"time":869803,"text":"is that ecological change need not always proceed"},{"time":873443,"text":"in one direction."},{"time":875906,"text":"It offers us the hope"},{"time":878342,"text":"that our silent spring"},{"time":880483,"text":"could be replaced by a raucous summer."}]},{"cues":[{"time":882814,"text":"Thank you."}]},{"cues":[{"time":884034,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}